---
description: code commenting requirements
alwaysApply: false
---

- Purpose-first
  - Explain WHY, trade-offs, and constraints; avoid restating behavior obvious from code or types.
  - Document invariants, preconditions/postconditions, side effects, and concurrency assumptions.

- Scope & placement
  - Keep comments close to relevant code.
  - Use top-level JSDoc for modules/classes/functions; inline block comments for complex logic.
  - All public APIs must have JSDoc; private members only if non-trivial.

- JSDoc/TSDoc conventions (JS/TS)
  - Use `/** ... */` with TSDoc tags.
  - Common tags: `@param`, `@returns`, `@throws`, `@remarks`, `@example`, `@see`, `@deprecated`, `@defaultValue`, `@internal`.
  - Specify thrown errors with `@throws` and conditions.
  - Provide minimal runnable or edge-case examples with `@example`.

- Maintenance & hygiene
  - Update or remove comments when code changes.
  - No secrets/PII in comments.
  - For temporary workarounds or technical debt, use:
    - `// TODO(scope): reason | tracking: URL | deadline: YYYY-MM-DD`
    - `// HACK: reason | revert-criteria | tracking: URL`

- Style
  - English only; concise, declarative tone.
  - Avoid self-evident comments or duplication of type info.
  - Keep line length ≤ 100 chars.

- Performance & complexity
  - Note complexity, performance assumptions, and fallback strategies.

- Concurrency & I/O
  - Indicate concurrency model, atomicity, idempotency, retry/timeout/cancel policies.

- Tooling integration
  - JSDoc should be compatible with Typedoc/TS Server for API generation.
  - Critical modules should include a short “design note” describing goals, non-goals, and trade-offs.
